# .privacy-allow — declare intentionally-synthetic data so the guard stops
# flagging it. COMMIT this file (unlike .privacy-patterns, which is per-clone
# and gitignored). What's synthetic is a property of the repo, the same for
# every clone, so it's versioned with the repo and reviewable in a diff.
#
# Declare VALUES, never paths. Realistic demo data is realistic ON PURPOSE — a
# sample LAN IP, a fake MAC, a canonical example key. A regex can't tell those
# from a real leak, so the repo declares them. Crucially we declare the exact
# VALUE, not the file or directory it lives in: excluding a whole `tests/**`
# path would also blind the guard to a real secret pasted into a test — which
# is exactly how a real device serial once slipped through. So the guard scans
# everything and suppresses a finding only when the matched text EXACTLY equals
# a value listed here. An unknown identifier in any path still fires.
#
# Format: one literal value per line. `#` comments and blank lines ignored.
# The value must equal exactly what a pattern matches:
#
#   192.168.1.50                # a sample LAN IP
#   00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E           # a demo MAC
#   AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE        # the canonical AWS example key
#   Samsung FAKESERIAL00        # vendor-serial rule matches brand + serial...
#   FAKESERIAL00                # ...and the bare-serial check matches just the serial
#   noreply@example.com         # a known-safe address
#
# Read by BOTH scripts/hooks/pre-commit and scripts/audit-privacy.sh, so the
# commit gate and the history audit agree. For a match found by GITLEAKS inside
# demo data instead, add it to [allowlist] in .gitleaks.toml.
